============ Patient Management System ============

Overview:

This project simulates a patient management system which would be used in a medical clinic. This system manages two
main features:

1. Patient History - historical records of patient visits
2. Waiting Room - a queue of patients waiting to be seen

Two data structures are used to implement this system:

1. Queue (FIFO) - used in the waiting room service
2. Doubly Linked List (DLL) - used in the patient history service

Why a Queue (FIFO) is appropriate for Waiting Room service?

A Queue is an ideal data structure for managing a waiting room because it follows the First-In-First-Out (FIFO)
principle. In a medical clinic, patients are normally seen in the same order they arrive. The queue structure naturally
models this behavior.

Operations used in the waiting room include:

- Add Patient → Patient joins the end of the queue.
- Serve Next Patient → The patient at the front of the queue is removed and served.
- Emergency Insertion → Allows inserting a patient at a specific position when necessary.

Using a queue ensures the waiting room behaves in a fair and predictable order and protects against duplicate entries.

FIFO Principle

FIFO stands for First-In-First-Out. This means that the first element inserted into the queue will be the
first one removed.

Example:

Patient arrival order - 1. Alice 2. Billy 3. Charlie
Queue structure - Front → Alice → Billy → Charlie → Back
When the doctor calls a patient - Alice is served first
Then Alice is removed - Front → Billy → Charlie → Back

This system ensures patients are treated in the order they arrived.

What would happen if a stack was used instead of a queue?

A stack follows the last in first out (LIFO) principle, this means the last patient to arrive would be the first
to be seen by the doctor.

Example with stack:

Patient arrival order - 1. Alice 2. Billy 3. Charlie
Stack order - Top → Charlie → Billy → Alice
When the doctor calls a patient - Charlie is served first

This would create an unfair waiting system, because the newest patient would always jump ahead of earlier patients.
Therefor using a stack would be inappropriate for a medical clini system.

Why a doubly linked list is appropriate for Patient History service.

A Doubly Linked List (DLL) is used for patient history service because it allows efficient navigation in both directions
of the list.

Each node in a doubly linked list contains:

A reference to the next record
A reference to the previous record

This structure allows the system to:

Move forward through patient records
Move backward through patient records
Keep track of a current record

In the program, this is used to implement the history navigation menu, where users can move to the next or previous
record in the list. This behavior is similar to how users browse browser history or undo/redo functionality.

What would happen if Next and Previous pointers were not updated?

When manipulating a doubly linked list, it is important to correctly update both the next and previous pointers.

If these pointers are not updated properly, several problems can occur:

1. Broken Links
    - Some nodes may become unreachable.

2. Infinite Loops
    - Incorrect references could cause the list to cycle endlessly.

3. Navigation Errors
    - Moving forward or backward through records could fail.

4. Data Loss
    - Some records may appear to disappear from the list.

Correct pointer management ensures the integrity of the list structure.

Why a Doubly Linked List works better than an Array or Array List?

Although arrays and ArrayLists can store data, they are not ideal for this type of navigation system.

Array/ArrayList Limitations:

Arrays and ArrayLists require index management to move forward or backward - index++ and index--

This means the program must always track the current index manually. Also, arrays have fixed sizes and insertions
in the middle of the list require shifting elements.

Advantages of Doubly Linked Lists

A Doubly Linked List provides:

- Direct next and previous navigation
- Dynamic size
- No shifting of elements
- Efficient insertion

Each node knows its neighbors, making navigation very natural. For a record history system, this makes a DLL the
most suitable structure.

Test Cases Explanation

PatientHistory Tests

Test: testAddRecords()

Purpose:

- Verifies that records can be successfully added to the history.

What it checks:

- After adding two records, the history size should be 2.

This ensures the addRecord() method correctly links nodes in the DLL.

Test: testNavigation()

Purpose:

Verifies correct forward and backward navigation in the history.

Steps tested:

- Add three records
- Move to the oldest record
- Navigate forward
- Navigate backward

Expected results:

- Oldest → r1
- Next → r2
- Next → r3
- Next → null
- Previous → r2

This confirms that the next and previous pointers work correctly.

Test: testBoundaryProtection()

Purpose:

Ensures the program does not move beyond the list boundaries.

Example:

If there is only one record - previousRecord() → null and nextRecord() → null
This protects against navigation errors

Test: testEmptyHistoryNavigation()

Purpose:

Ensures the system behaves correctly when the history is empty.

Expected behavior:

- getCurrent() → null
- nextRecord() → null
- previousRecord() → null

This protects against null point errors

WaitingRoom Tests

Test: testFifoServiceOrder()

Purpose:

Verifies that the queue follows the FIFO principle.

Steps:

1. Add Alice
2. Add Billy
3. Serve next patient

Expected result: Alice is served first

This confirms that serveNextPatient() removes the first patient in the queue.

Test: testEmergencyInsertion()

Purpose:

Verifies that emergency patients can be inserted into a specific position.

Steps:

- Add Alice
- Add Billy
- Insert emergency patient at position 1

Expected queue: Alice → Emergency → Billy

This test confirms the emergency insertion works.

Test: testInvalidEmergencyInsertion()

Purpose:

Ensures invalid insertion positions are rejected.

Example:

Trying to insert at position 1 when the queue is empty should return: false

This protects the system from invalid inputs.

Test: testServeEmptyQueue()

Purpose:

Ensures serving from an empty queue does not cause errors.

Expected result: serveNextPatient() → null

This confirms the method safely handles an empty waiting room queue.

Suggested Future Improvements

1. Persistent Storage

Currently, the program only stores data in memory only.

Future versions should store data using:

- Files
- Databases

This would allow patient data to persist between program runs. For this project I decided to keep it simple as we only
needed to show proof that the program functions correctly, proper data storage can be added later if this was a
real project.

2. Patient Priority System

Instead of only inserting emergency patients manually, the system could implement a priority queue that automatically
prioritizes severe cases. Again for this project I wanted to reduce the complexity of building out a priority system
but that can certainly be added later.

3. Interface Improvements

The waiting room display could be improved by formatting patients in a format which is easier to read.

Conclusion

This project demonstrates practical use of data structures in a real-world scenario.

- Queues effectively model waiting room behavior using FIFO ordering.
- Doubly Linked Lists provide efficient navigation for patient history.
- JUnit tests ensure system reliability and correctness.

The system is modular, tested, and designed in a way that can be extended with additional features in the future.